<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / International Capital Markets: Grand Met looks to US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRAND Metropolitan, the British leisure group, yesterday joined the flood of
companies taking advantage of low US interest rates to raise money in the
domestic US bond market as it moved to refinance Dollars 800m of its
short-term debt.
Grand Met issued seven, 12-and 30-year bonds to repay some of the commercial
paper it has issued to launch acquisitions in recent years, including its
takeover of US group Pillsbury in 1989.
Corporate borrowers have benefited from the falling differential between the
rates paid by borrowers and the US government. Last summer, Grand Met
launched 20-year bonds at a spread of more than 90 basis points over US
Treasuries, compared with a spread now of 77 basis points on its 30-year
bonds.
Due to falling US rates, the company had been able to issue longer-dated
bonds at an all-in yield of around 1 percentage point less than a year ago.
