<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Peru parades captured rebel leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FLABBY, middle-aged and bespectacled, wearing an identification tag like a
common criminal, the leader of Peru's feared Sendero Luminoso (Shining Path)
guerrillas has been paraded before the Peruvian people on television in a
bid to destroy the aura that has built up around him during 13 years in
hiding.
President Alberto Fujimori personally presented the television images of
Latin America's most wanted and feared insurgent.
Mr Abimael Guzman Reynoso - alias 'Presidente Gonzalo' - had been captured
in a counter-terrorist police raid on a Lima suburban house 24 hours
earlier. His detention, along with several other high-ranking Sendero
officials, is a big success for the Fujimori government, and one of the few
bits of good news for Peru since the April 5 institutional coup when Mr
Fujimori dissolved Congress and suspended the constitution.
Mr Guzman's capture allowed the Peruvian president to justify his tough and
much-criticised counter-insurgency policy and to repeat his determination to
defeat Peru's terrorist groups before 1995, when his term of office
officially ends.
Popular mythology had attributed Mr Guzman with almost magical powers to
move around Peru unseen. A home-made video, shot more than three years ago,
had provided the only previous dent in the guerrilla leader's image - it
showed him inebriated, carousing with sycophantic followers and dancing to
the music of Zorba the Greek. In Sunday's broadcast he appeared fumbling
with his trouser buttons after being told to take off his shirt, apparently
meekly obeying police instructions.
'This is not the revolutionary hero fabricated by myth,' scoffed Mr Fujimori
in his Sunday night address. 'What we are seeing here is a monster.' He
dubbed Mr Guzman 'sinister, malevolent. . . a diabolic genius. . . the
henchman of the drugs trade'.
The president accused Sendero of accumulating vast funds through the cocaine
trade with which to finance 'Sendero ambassadors' in a number of European
countries, including Britain, France, Belgium, Spain and Sweden. And he
charged Mr Guzman with 'genocide', citing massacres in shanty-towns and
rural communities. 'He is just as much a war criminal as the second world
war fascists,' Mr Fujimori said.
Sendero's leader, like other Peruvians now under arrest on charges of
terrorism, will face summary trial by military tribunal. Modifications to
the penal code in the wake of Sendero's car-bomb attacks in July mean
terrorists are now considered 'traitors to the fatherland'.
Although the death penalty for terrorism has wide popular support, it has
not yet been enshrined in government policy. At a news conference yesterday,
however, Mr Fujimori said: 'The law establishes at this time that the
maximum penalty in this case is life imprisonment. But we must also listen
to what the public demands.' When pressed, he said his personal opinion was
that Mr Guzman deserved the death penalty and that he 'would study' its
application.
The capture of their leader, widely recognised as a brilliant military
strategist, is a heavy blow for Sendero. But the organisation, according to
Mr Enrique Bernales, former president of the Peruvian Senate commission on
violence, is 'a Maoist, clandestine party with a quasi-military structure.
They must already be activating contingency plans of tactical retreat and
reconstruction'.
The armed forces and police are braced for a violent response from the
guerrillas. Security has been stepped up in the capital.
An encouraging aspect of Mr Guzman's capture is that it seems, however
briefly, to have created some desire for unity in a nation still deeply
divided by racial, class and income differences. Some prominent politicians
previously hostile to Mr Fujimori's de facto regime are now calling for
'national reconciliation'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
