<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Schroder Ventures apologises to CINVen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCHRODER Ventures yesterday made a highly unusual public apology to a
competitor, CINVen, the venture capital arm of the Coal Board's in-house
fund manager.
The venture capital arm of Schroders Plc in a press statement admitted that
one of its executives had circulated a document saying that CINVen managers
'received exceptional and unfair returns'.
Schroder Ventures said yesterday it 'unreservedly repudiates this document
which contains major errors of fact'. It said the document was the source of
press articles criticising the way CINVen managers are paid. CINVen also
manages the venture capital portion of the British Rail and Barclays Bank
pension funds.
The move comes amid rising competition between fund managers following the
sharp shrinkage of new investment in venture capital. An agreement between
Schroders and CINVen meant neither party would make any comment beyond a
limited press statement. However, CINVen had made it clear it would take
legal action if a public apology were not forthcoming.
An article in the Financial Times on August 27, which CINVen said was 'fair
and accurate', pointed out that CINVen fund managers are able to profit from
a co-investment scheme which allows them to purchase a portion of the 'sweet
equity' used to finance management buy-outs without having to invest in the
less risky but lower-yielding loan stock.
However, the Schroder document contained further allegations, not printed by
the Financial Times, which were yesterday withdrawn.
Sweet equity is the highest-risk but potentially most profitable security
issued in connection with venture capital.
The practice of allowing managers to co-invest in sweet equity is not
uncommon in the fund management industry but many investors' advisers frown
on the practice. However, CINVen's structure does not allow it to offer the
most common alternative, known as carried interest, in which managers earn
roughly 20 per cent of all the venture pool's profits. This can be more
lucrative than co-investment schemes limited to sweet equity.
Remuneration structures in the venture capital industry have recently been
under pressure from investors who argue that some fund managers rewards are
not tied closely enough to performance or the skills to do the job. Several
of the latest venture capital pooled funds have had to promise higher
returns to investors before fund managers could share in the profits.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
