<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Mellon buys The Boston Co for Dollars 1.4bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHEARSON Lehman Brothers, the Wall Street securities firm owned by American
Express, is selling The Boston Company, a private banking and investment
services company, to Pittsburgh-based Mellon Bank for Dollars 1.45bn (Pounds
730m).
Yesterday's announcement triggered fresh speculation on Wall Street that the
disposal might be the prelude to the sale by American Express of Shearson
itself or an offer of its stock to the public. American Express has
repeatedly denied any such plan.
Shearson announced in early August it planned to sell The Boston Company,
which has loans and other assets of around Dollars 9bn and is involved in
mutual fund administration, trust and custody services for institutional
investors, institutional investment management and private banking for
wealthy individuals.
The acquisition expands Mellon's sizeable position in these fields. It will
become a leading US provider of mutual fund administration services.
The deal reinforces Mellon's strategy of focusing on revenues from the
provision of services as much as on lending activities.
The strategy was put in place in the late 1980s after Mellon, suffered
serious loan problems in the property and energy markets.
The Dollars 1.45bn Shearson will get for The Boston Company is higher than
market expectations and underscores the premium prices commanded by fund
management and investment services companies.
Shearson expects to book an after-tax gain of about Dollars 150m from the
sale, which would reduce goodwill around Dollars 100m, increasing tangible
equity Dollars 250m.
The sale will cut Shearson's assets, boosting its equity-to-assets ratio
towards the level analysts say is necessary for American Express to sell the
company or float a tranche of its stock.
Mellon will pay Dollars 1.301bn in cash, Dollars 115m in the bank's common
stock and Dollars 37m in share warrants. It will fund the deal by issuing a
further Dollars 150m in common stock, Dollars 150m in perpetual preferred
stock and Dollars 815m in senior debt.
The bank said it expected to book a one-time after-tax charge of Dollars
112m for consolidation expenses.
Mellon shares fell Dollars 1 1/8 to close at Dollars 40 1/4 in New York.
American Express rose Dollars 1 to close at Dollars 22 3/4.
</TEXT>
