<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Labour's Maastricht dissidents pull back from clash with
Smith
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S deep-rooted internal divisions over Maastricht were patched over
yesterday when critics of the treaty shied away from a direct confrontation
with Mr John Smith, the new party leader.
The party's national executive committee postponed a debate on European
policy until after the French referendum on Sunday. The leadership will then
draw up a formal position to present to the shadow cabinet and NEC the
following Wednesday.
The decision by senior shadow cabinet ministers not to press for immediate
policy changes is likely to defuse the row in the short-term. However,
profound differences between Labour's keen Europeans and those determined to
see substantial changes in the Maastricht treaty are unlikely to dissolve.
Mr Bryan Gould, the senior frontbencher who challenged Mr Smith for the
leadership, made clear before the meeting that he viewed the weekend
realignment in the exchange rate mechanism as likely to exacerbate rather
than relieve economic tensions in the longer term.
In interviews with broadcasters after the meeting, Mr Smith made clear that
he expected the three members of the shadow cabinet who have criticised his
strategy over Maastricht and sterling to toe the line once a formal policy
position is agreed.
Dismissing the likelihood of a confrontation with Mr Gould, he nonetheless
signalled that he will act firmly to enforce a common stance. 'I don't think
there will be a case of any of my colleagues not accepting the collective
responsibility they have been living with for years,' he said.
Officials also said the leader would not cede to pressure for a referendum
on the treaty and continued to oppose any suggestion of a sterling
devaluation.
The truce came after a personal appeal from Mr Smith at the national
executive meeting, called to approve a new document - Agenda for Change -
setting out Labour's post-election goals.
In consequence, Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, agreed to
withdraw amendments to the document's section on Europe which aimed to keep
open the policy option of devaluation and which required democratic
constraints on a European central bank.
Describing the meeting as constructive, Mr Blunkett said there was a case
for a breathing space until the French referendum was completed. 'It seemed
sensible to heal wounds and ensure we have a positive way forward,' he said.
Mr Dennis Skinner, the veteran leftwinger, mocked the shadow cabinet
dissidents, however, claiming they were merely adopting leftwing postures
before the NEC elections at the party conference later this month.
The Agenda for Change document, agreed yesterday, intends to address the
causes of Labour's election defeat by presenting the party as the champion
of ordinary people's goals and ambitions.
</TEXT>
