FT  15 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than a quarter of all British seven year olds fail to reach minimum
standards in reading tests. BBC2's Education Special (7.50) investigates a
new teaching method called Reading Recovery, already tried in New Zealand,
the US, Australia and Canada which, it is claimed, takes at most 20 weeks to
bring the worst pupils up to the average.
In Floyd On Spain (8.30 BBC2) Keith Floyd conducts his happy gastronauts
through the culinary delights of the Costa Blanca. They include paella and
roast suckling pig.
If you want to see yet another programme about Saint Roddick, fragrant boss
of The Body Shop, she is featured in the last of BBC2's series The John Bull
Business (9.30) which warns against adopting new technology without
accepting the need for change in work methods.
C4 gives the first television screening to Mike Leigh's highly praised 1990
drama, Life Is Sweet, in which Jim Broadbent and Alison Steadman play a
suburban couple with two grown-up daughters: Natalie, a plumber, and Nicola,
a bulimic and would-be feminist.
