<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / The Liberal Democrats At Harrogate: Wilson rejects pacts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A VIGOROUS warning that the Liberal Democrats should resist 'siren calls'
for any form of political realignment came yesterday from Mr Des Wilson, who
was the party's campaigns co-ordinator during the April general election,
Alison Smith writes.
At a party rally last night, Mr Wilson said that it was politically
unrealistic to discuss deals with other parties, given the Labour party's
present attitude.
It represented a destructive waste of time that should be spent discussing
policies that were important, and also denied the party's historic role as
'the upholder of principle in politics.'
'What's the point of compromising so much to get power that you haven't the
freedom to do what's right when you've got it?' he asked.
He condemned the Labour party for reacting too readily to election defeats
by trying to become an even safer option to the electorate than the
Conservatives.
Mr Wilson hinted that the speech after the general election in which Mr
Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, raised the possibility of dialogue with
other parties, might have been an error.
He rejected the idea that disappointment with the election result might have
given rise to talk about co-operation with other organisations.
Instead, Mr Wilson - who left his unpaid post with the party after the
election - insisted that the party's 'success' in winning 20 seats and just
under 20 per cent of the popular vote across the country was consistent with
the 'outside hope' throughout the planning and carrying out of the campaign.
He urged the party to retain its independence and ability to face up to
difficult questions.
Much like a pressure group, he said, having a platform and organisation from
which to campaign could lead to changes even without conventional political
power.
