<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Water watchdog hits back at 'alarmist' Greenpeace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Rivers Auth-ority, the water industry's environmental watchdog,
yesterday accused Greenpeace, the campaigning group, of issuing 'alarmist
propaganda' over river and sea pollution. It said Greenpeace had tried to
'force the world back through time'.
The attack by Lord Crickhowell, the former Cons-ervative cabinet minister
who chairs the authority, was a response to a month-long Greenpeace campaign
against the authority's system of issuing permits for discharging waste into
rivers. Greenpeace calls the system 'legal pollution'.
Tomorrow Greenpeace will publish a report called Filthy Fifty, listing what
it says are the 50 industrial plants licensed to discharge the most toxic
pollution into rivers and estuaries.
Lord Crickhowell's remarks also come a week before environment ministers
from the UK and 13 other countries meet in Paris to sign a treaty on marine
pollution.
He accused Greenpeace of treating the authority as an enemy. 'Alarmist
propaganda and publicity stunts may grab the headlines, but it is pressure
through the pollution-control system that is forcing the industry to clean
up its act,' he said.
The discharge permits issued by the authority were 'licences to protect' and
enabled industry to operate without polluting, he added.
The authority has also been attacked by water and sewerage companies that
have claimed that some of its standards have been unnecessarily and
expensively too high. Ofwat, the water industry's economic watchdog, in last
months's report on increases in water bills, also put pressure on the
authority to examine whether its interpretation of some environmental
legislation is too stringent.
Mr Paul Horsman, Greenpeace's waste campaigner, said: 'We are simply calling
for the elimination of substances that the Paris Commission (an
international conference on discharging waste at sea) called for in 1974.
The Thames now supports fish mainly because the removal of sewage has
improved the oxygen content, but you still can't eat the fish.'
</TEXT>
