<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / ITC defends proposed arrangements for ITV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE independent Television Commission yesterday defended proposed
arrangements for the ITV network yesterday in spite of implicit criticism of
some of the suggestions by the Office of Fair Trading.
The commission emphasised in its formal response to the OFT that the 1990
Broadcasting Act allows ITV companies both to broadcast and to make
programmes, and that licences have been granted on that basis.
'The competition test should not therefore be interpreted in a way which
treats vertical integration of this kind as either undesirable in practice
or unacceptable in principle,' the ITC says.
The OFT has a statutory responsibility to ensure that arrangements for the
ITV network are fair, including fair access for independent producers to the
commissioning system.
Last month the OFT said it had identified a number of potentially
anti-competitive elements in the new ITV networking arrangements. They
included proposals that prevent independent producers contracting directly
with the ITV network, and ITV insistence that it wants to buy programme
rights for 10 years with a further five-year option.
On contracting, the ITC says responsibility for compliance with regulatory
requirements must rest with ITV companies because the ITC can impose
sanctions only on its licensees.
The ITC also says that when a broadcaster fully funds a programme 'there
should be a period in which it alone can benefit without the programme being
available to UK broadcasting competitors'. The ITC does not, however,
suggest that period should be 15 years.
The OFT made clear in last month's consultative document that it would not
reach firm conclusions until the outcome of further discussions had been
fully analysed. Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, will
make a full report on networking arrangements by December.
At least 100 jobs are to go at the recently merged Yorkshire and Tyne-Tees
Television. At present, the group employs about 1,400 people. The job losses
will remove duplication in administration and programme-making.
</TEXT>
