<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / NVQs criticised as too restrictive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY of the new National Vocational Qualifications are too narrow and
job-specific, an Institute of Manpower Studies report said yesterday.
The report - which the institute said was produced under contract with the
Department of Employment - draws particularly on experience of NVQs in the
construction industry.
NVQs, the new national system of assessment based on competence in the
workplace, are being introduced across the whole spectrum of employment.
Employer-led bodies, called industry lead bodies, advised on the contents of
the new qualifications which were drawn up by the National Council for
Vocational Qualifications.
There are several criticisms of the qualifications in the report, including
the view that they suffer from poor general recognition and a lack of
information to employers, employees and training providers. 'As yet, most
people cannot even conceptualise what owning an NVQ means,' the report says.
'Many NVQs are limited and too mechanistic and restrictive,' it says. 'Often
their educational content has been squeezed out along with pedagogic
concerns.'
The study says the narrowness of employer-defined competence training
highlights the conflict between the short-term needs of employers for very
specific skills and the long-term interests and training needs of trainees,
the industry, and the economy. 'It brings into question whether it is in the
interests of individuals to have such narrow and partial training.'
The report adds that in their present form NVQs are unlikely to change
either the incentive for employers to train people or the take-up of
vocational training.
Will National Vocational Qualifications Work? IMS Report No 228. IMS,
Mantell Buildings, University of Sussex, Falmer, Brighton, East Sussex, BN1
9RF. Pounds 12.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
