<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Engineering faces decline in orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ORDERS TO engineering companies in the West Midlands, traditionally the
heart of UK manufacturing, have slowed again after a brief surge in the
spring, dissipating the belief that economic recovery has started.
The Engineering Employers Federation in the West Midlands, which surveyed
520 companies, reported yesterday that, in the three months to August, 39
per cent of companies had seen orders decline, compared with 25 per cent in
the three months to May.
The proportion of companies receiving more orders shrank to 31 per cent in
the August quarter from 46 per cent in the May quarter.
Mr David Botterill, the federation's regional chief executive, said:
'Similarly, more companies are now experiencing a reduction in the
utilisation of their manufacturing capacity than was the case in the spring.
More plans for capital investment appear to have been shelved for the time
being as cashflows worsen.'
Evidence of the retarded recovery from recession has dented business
confidence. More than half the companies in the federation's West Midlands
May survey had expected an improvement in orders - now the proportion has
fallen to 30 per cent.
</TEXT>
