FT  15 SEP 92 / Accountants are reprimanded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE FIRMS of chartered accountants have been reprimanded by their
disciplinary body for breaches of investment business regulations.
RA McLeod of Windsor, was fined Pounds 500 and ordered to pay Pounds 250 in
costs by the disciplinary committee of the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales following hearings last month.
The firm failed to give adequate warnings of the risks involved to a client
relating to certain investments, failed to send engagement letters and
failed to keep proper records in accordance with regulations.
Sowerbutts &amp; Co, based in Camberley, Surrey, was fined Pounds 500 and
ordered to pay Pounds 250 costs for a series of breaches of regulations
including failing to keep adequate records.
Bygott Burn of Grimsby, Humberside, was reprimanded and ordered to pay
Pounds 250 costs for handling a money from an investment business client
when not authorised to do so.
In addition, Mr Peter Downey of Horner, Downey &amp; Co in Bromborough,
Merseyside, was reprimanded, fined Pounds 1,000 and ordered to pay Pounds
500 costs for 13 issues surrounding the audit of a limited company since
1986.
He failed to prepare the accounts in accordance with the format laid down in
the Companies Acts, statements of standard accounting practice and auditing
standards.
