<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / UN gives go-ahead to boost Bosnian force
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS at the UN, FRANCES WILLIAMS and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, GENEVA, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations Security Council last night approved plans to send about
5,000 more peacekeeping troops - including British soldiers - to the former
Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Hercegovina.
The UN vote came after heavy fighting flared up again yesterday in the
Bosnian capital of Sarajevo, which has been besieged by Serb forces since
April. The upsurge in fighting cast further doubts on plans for
international peace talks to resume in Geneva on Friday.
The extra UN troops - already offered by Britain, other European countries
and Canada - are being sent to help protect relief convoys and ensure the
safety of Moslem and Croat detainees freed by Serb captors from prison
camps. The UK has offered up to 1,800 soldiers.
The UN already has 15,000 peacekeeping troops in the former Yugoslavia,
including 1,500 in Bosnia-Hercegovina.
The Security Council voted 12-0 to increase the size of the force, with
three member countries abstaining - China, India and Zimbabwe.
The resolution also stressed the importance of air security measures, such
as a ban on military flights over Bosnia by the Serbian-controlled Yugoslav
federal air force. Rapid implementation of such measures could 'reinforce
the security' of international humanitarian operations in Bosnia, it said.
Meanwhile Serbs and Moslems blamed each other for the latest violence in
Sarajevo - the worst outbreak for several weeks - and for attempting to
torpedo the peace talks due to be held in Geneva.
At least four people were killed and 50 wounded, and reports from the city
said heavy artillery had been used despite last weekend's agreement to put
it under UN supervision to determine who was firing first.
Mr Rusmir Jahic, commander of units loyal to the Bosnian government, said
the old part of the city was shelled, and mortars had fallen on the Holiday
Inn, where many journalists are staying.
Bosnian commanders also reported that the suburbs of Hrasno, Breka and
Bjelava were under fire.
Mr Ermin Taric, a Serb, and one of the Bosnian commanders in Hrasno, said
Serb irregulars were trying to gain control of the suburbs by using tanks.
He added that the local childrens' hospital was also shelled.
Before the upsurge in violence, the Bosnian president, Mr Alija Izetbegovic,
wrote to Mr Cyrus Vance, the UN mediator, to say his government would not
attend the peace talks because of continued fighting. Mr Radovan Karadzic,
the Bosnian Serb leader, has also threatened to pull out of the talks if an
air exclusion zone over Bosnia is imposed.
Mr Vance and Lord Owen, co-chairmen of the international peace conference,
are insisting that leaders of the three Bosnian communities attend the
Geneva talks.
Mr Fred Eckhard, spokesman for the two co-chairmen, said that on their visit
to the region last week Mr Vance and Lord Owen had got 'solemn, personal and
unconditional commitments' from all the warring parties that they would go
to Geneva. Mr Vance, who represents the UN, and Lord Owen, the European
Community representative, 'expect all sides to be present at senior level on
Friday', Mr Eckhard said.
Representatives of the three communities are due to meet UN officials in
Geneva today to agree security and confidence-building measures that would
permit resumption of a UN airlift into Sarajevo. The airlift was suspended
nearly a fortnight ago after the downing of an Italian transport aircraft,
apparently by missiles, and food stocks in Sarajevo are dwindling.
Mr Eckhard, briefing reporters, said UN monitors were now based at 11 heavy
weapons sites controlled by Bosnian Serbs around Sarajevo. This was in
accordance with the agreement between Mr Karadzic and the conference
chairmen which puts heavy weapons around four Bosnian cities under UN
supervision.
There had been 'some resistance' by local Serb commanders at Bihac and Jajce
to inclusion of 82mm mortars, as the accord stipulates.
This, and the status of heavy weapons near Gorazde, where Serb forces have
lifted their siege, are now the subject of negotiations with UNPROFOR, the
UN monitoring force.
UNPROFOR was also negotiate with Bosnian government forces in Sarajevo to
put their heavy weapons under UN observation, Mr Eckhard said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
