<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Irish to launch new phone tap investigation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A police investigation is to be launched into Ireland's latest political
scandal - the tapping of the telephone of Mr John Bruton, the leader of the
main opposition party, Fine Gael, writes Tim Coone in Dublin.
Mr Patrick Culligan, the Irish police commissioner, ordered the inquiry
yesterday after a Sunday newspaper published transcripts of three alleged
conversations between Mr Bruton and senior party colleagues that took place
last January.
The conversations related to revelations by a former justice minister about
telephone tapping that occurred 10 years earlier. The January incident led
to the resignation of Mr Charles Haughey, the prime minister, who was
replaced by Mr Albert Reynolds.
During the leadership contest, Mr Reynolds complained that he suspected he
was under surveillance. Mr Padraig Flynn, appointed justice minister by Mr
Reynolds, said yesterday: 'As far as my information is concerned, certainly
there was no authorisation by the minister insofar as any illegal tapping of
this kind.'
</TEXT>
