<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Kohl in secret visit to Bundesbank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER, DAVID MARSH and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, LONDON, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR HELMUT KOHL, the German chancellor, paid a secret visit to the Bundesbank
in Frankfurt on Friday to discuss a realignment of currencies in the
European exchange rate mechanism and a cut in German interest rates.
Confirmation of the visit, which also involved Mr Theo Waigel, finance
minister, and Mr Horst Kohler, state secretary for finance, emerged
yesterday.
It is likely to fuel accusations that the government put unprecedented
political pressure on the independent central bank to persuade it to relax
its high interest rate policy.
Bundesbank officials, however, are adamant that they were the ones who had
to persuade the chancellor and his finance minister to support a full ERM
realignment, hitherto blocked by other European Community governments such
as France.
Indeed, senior government officials yesterday maintained that Germany was
ready to cut its interest rates - in exchange for a realignment - more than
a week before the deal was finalised on Sunday.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, Bundesbank president, said in Kiel last night: 'It is
a misunderstanding to maintain that we were forced into interest rate cuts.
We have accompanied several realignments, including that of 1987, with an
interest rate reduction.'
Responding to the charge that the Bundesbank's independence had been 'lost',
Mr Schlesinger said the central bank had never had full independence under
fixed exchange rates, either in the Bretton Woods system until 1973 or in
the European Monetary System.
A number of commentators expressed alarm at the apparent loss of
independence, including Mr Hans-Peter Stihl, president of the German Chamber
of Industry and Commerce. 'The chamber will be watching to see how the
independence of the Bundesbank is protected,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
