<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / Steelworkers in recognition row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STEEL union, the Iron and Steel Trades Confederation, which has never
been derecognised in its 100-year-plus history, is facing its second
derecognition contest.
A bitter industrial dispute at the Spartan Redheugh steel mill in Gateshead
has led to the sacking of all the blue-collar staff and the recruitment of
non-union workers.
Even more serious for the union, the Canadian-owned Sheerness Steel, based
on the Isle of Sheppey in Kent, in the spring successfully withdrew
recognition from the 700-strong workforce at the same time as introducing
personal contracts, single status between white and blue-collar staff, and
performance-related pay.
Mr Ian Scobbie, the Sheerness ISTC official, said that the workforce was
unhappy about the decision to move to personal contracts, but with very high
local unemployment it had been difficult to win support for industrial
action.
He said derecognition also applied to representing members in individual
disciplinary cases.
Mr Hugh Billot, Sheerness Steel personnel director, told the magazine
Personnel Management Plus that after moving to single status and personal
contracts, 'we realised we no longer had anything to discuss with the
unions'. He said other companies had shown an interest in what the company
had done. The ISTC said there was no evidence for a wave of derecognition
cases.
Bifu, the finance union, has won recognition rights at the North of England
Building Society after a long battle with a company staff association. Bifu
has won recognition as the result of a 'membership audit'. Discussions with
the conciliation service Acas established Bifu as the organisation with the
highest support.
</TEXT>
