<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / World Trade News: Bush faces clash over China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Senate is heading for a further confrontation with President Bush
after a vote yesterday to impose conditions next year on China's Most
Favoured Nation status.
The House has already passed legislation to renew China's MFN status - which
provides the lowest tariffs possible - only on condition it improves human
rights and trade behaviour and adheres to curbs on missile and nuclear
exports. The House is expected to muster the two-thirds vote it needs to
override a veto.
Senators yesterday passed a similar measure by a voice vote, leaving in
doubt the number of senators prepared to go against the president.
Meanwhile, US trade officials were yesterday continuing talks in Beijing on
market access. With the China merchandise trade surplus likely to exceed
Dollars 15bn (Pounds 7.6bn) this year, the Bush administration badly wants a
victory at the negotiating table to restrain the forces seeking to impose
conditions on MFN.
Alternatively, the president can impose sanctions on up to Dollars 3.9bn in
goods if no agreement on access is reached with China before October 10.
</TEXT>
