<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / The ERM and Maastricht: Japan rules out interest rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE officials yesterday dismissed suggestions that Japan should cut its
own interest rates but welcomed the realignment of European currencies and
the German decision to reduce rates.
Mr Tsutomu Hata, finance minister, said that Japanese interest rates were
already low and that there was no reason to cut them further.
'The cumulative effects from the past five discount rate cuts are emerging
steadily and (interest) rates are at useful levels,' he said.
Mr Mamoru Ozaki, vice- finance minister, said Germany was intending to stem
the recent rise in the value of the D-Mark, but added: 'This, however, will
not inspire us to alter our monetary policy.'
Japanese financial markets nonetheless rallied yesterday, partly on
expectation of a further easing of Japanese rates. The Nikkei index of the
Tokyo Stock Exchange closed up 363.71 points, at 18,471.40. Traders said the
rally was partly a response to the 800 point decline on Friday, but
sentiment was aided by the prospect of an international move towards lower
interest rates.
</TEXT>
