<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Wet weather helps Ransomes return to the
black with Pounds 2m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RANSOMES, the mowing machinery manufacturer, returned to the black in the
six months to June 30 but again passed its interim dividend.
The group reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 2.01m, compared with losses of
Pounds 767,000. Sales rose to Pounds 79.8m (Pounds 76.8m) and operating
profit increased by 42 per cent to Pounds 6.41m (Pounds 4.53m).
Mr Bob Dodsworth, chief executive, said the Pounds 2.3m cost of the
preference dividend and the continuing worldwide recession meant that the
group still could not afford to pay an ordinary dividend.
'We have turned the corner on the first half and July and August were better
than last year. But we still have a long way to go.'
Wetter weather in Europe helped consumer grass machinery to increase
operating profits to Pounds 2.01m (Pounds 614,000). 'The last three years
were very dry' said Mr Dodsworth. 'This year people have had to cut their
grass.'
Commercial grass machinery and industrial vehicles lifted operating profits
from Pounds 3.52m to Pounds 3.98m reflecting a reduction in the workforce
and tighter cost controls.
Another 80 jobs were shed across the group bringing the total below 2,000.
Small property disposals enabled the property division to increase operating
profits from Pounds 397,000 to Pounds 423,000.
Cost cutting and currency exchange movements helped reduce borrowings by
Pounds 16m to Pounds 73m, representing gearing of 190 per cent.
Mr Dodsworth said difficulties in exporting to the US and stiff US
competition arising from the weak dollar more than offset advantages of
exporting from US businesses.
Fully diluted earnings per share of 1.4p compared with losses of 1.6p.
</TEXT>
