<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Audit reform plan resisted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT should retain the requirement for small limited liability
companies to be audited, the president of the Chartered Association of
Certified Accountants said at the weekend.
In an outspoken address to the annual conference of the association, which
represents 30,000 accountants, Mr David Bishop called supporters of
abolition of the smaller-company audit 'wrong, outdated in their thinking
and nave.'
Mr Bishop, who is a partner with KPMG Peat Marwick, said the audit provided
protection for all those associated with a company and imposed disciplines
that helped rather than hindered businesses.
Earlier this year, the Department of Trade and Industry said it was
considering lifting the requirement for small companies, possibly those
below the Pounds 36,600 turnover VAT threshold.
The Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales and the
Chartered Institute of Management Accountants have been among the
organisations since then that have lent support to reform of the existing
system.
They say it is costly, irrelevant and contradictory in its present form.
However, the association, which has many members who perform audits on small
companies, has always stood out against abolition and has been lobbying the
government in the last few weeks for its retention.
</TEXT>
