<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / The Lex Column: Adjusting to reality
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Whatever the size of the cut in German interest rates we are promised from
this morning's Bundesbank meeting, there are two possible conclusions to be
drawn from the weekend's currency excitements.
One is that the European Monetary system has again become the system of
fixed but adjustable rates which its founders intended. In recent years, as
realignments became increasingly rare, Europe had seemed to be on its way
towards monetary union by inertia: now, the markets have forced a reversion
to flexibility. Fixed exchange rates will have to come about by fiat -
through the Maastricht treaty or some later reprise - rather than by
default.
A second conclusion might be that German interest rates are now, inexorably,
heading down - and with them, rates in the rest of Europe. On this view,
there might be a hiccup or two on the way, if the Bundesbank's backwoodsmen
were able to rally their forces, but the growing weakness of the German
economy would ensure that any re-tightening was momentary rather than
sustained.
For most markets, these two conclusions lead in directly contrary
directions. For over a year, investors have been expecting to treat the turn
in German interest rates as a buying signal. Yet the newly demonstrated
adjustability of the ERM makes weak currencies such as sterling that much
more vulnerable.
But even for stronger currencies, last night's realignment holds a message.
It places the responsibility for convergence on the shoulders of politicians
rather than central banks. The Maastricht ratification process has shown how
little prepared they are to carry that burden.
There is one market, however, for which only half of this pair of matched
conclusions applies. The dollar stands to gain from a sustained reduction in
German interest rates, but is exempt from Europe's convergence neurosis. If
the markets really believe that the turn has come in D-Mark interest rates,
the dollar will show the impact most clearly.
One other market will be particularly sensitive in the coming days - not
least because it will be the one the Bundesbank watches most closely. The
German bond market will doubtless rally in the wake of the cut in short-term
rates.
The critical question is how far that rally will go, and whether it succumbs
to second thoughts. A weak rally, or one that is reversed in a matter of
weeks, would be a vote of no confidence in the Bundesbank's ability to
pursue anti-inflationary policies independent of political pressure. That
would not reverse the medium-term direction of European interest rates; but
it would put a floor under them well above the levels which are currently
failing to reignite the US.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
