<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Observer: Absent friends
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Where will you be on the day French voters decide Europe's future? If you
follow the example of the community's ruling elite, you will be at least
3,000 miles away.
The twelve's finance ministers and central bankers - expected to calm the
chaos on the financial markets if the French deliver a Gaullist snub to
Maastricht - will be in Washington for the IMF's annual jamboree.
The pals from the EC's foreign ministries will be just up the road in New
York attending the general assembly of the United Nations when the votes are
counted on September 20.
Presumably they'll be able to spare a few moments from the cocktails to
assure us that Europe is safe in their hands.
</TEXT>
