</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECEIVERS at Berkertex Group, the bridalwear manufacturer and retailer,
have moved quickly to secure the sale of one of its largest subsidiaries,
Fifth Avenue, a leading supplier to the fashion mail order catalogue trade.
Mr Paul Fabian and Mr Brian Worth, two of the company's managers, are
staging a buy-out preserving 31 jobs. This move is backed by 3i, the venture
capital group, and Barclays Bank.
The purchase price was not disclosed but it 'substantially exceeded the
company's break-up value', the receivers said.
Mr Christopher Morris, the receiver from Touche Ross, said Fifth Avenue was
profitable but had been dragged down by the collapse last Friday of its
heavily-indebted parent company. Last year Fifth Avenue's sales wereover
Pounds 13m and in the current year are running at more than Pounds 9m.
Receivers have been criticised recently for selling businesses to existing
managers before the assets recoverable for creditors can be fully assessed.
But Mr Morris defended a quick sale in this particular case. 'This was an
evaporating business. By Monday or Tuesday of next week there would have
been nothing left to sell.'
