<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Warning on Bosnia peace strategy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED Nations and European Community officials will this week start
implementing a three-pronged strategy aimed at ending the war in
Bosnia-Hercegovina, officials in Belgrade said at the weekend, write Judy
Dempsey in Belgrade and Lionel Barber in Hatfield.
But they warned that the process will be slow. The strategy involves linking
political talks at the Geneva conference on the former Yugoslavia, with a
massive humanitarian aid operation in Bosnia, and an extended monitoring
mission to stem fighting.
It follows discussions over the past few days between Mr Cyrus Vance and
Lord Owen, joint chairmen of the Geneva conference, and Croatian, Bosnian
and Serbian leaders. The EC yesterday expressed guarded optimism about the
peace efforts and agreed to refrain from introducing tougher diplomatic and
economic sanctions.
Mr Douglas Hurd, British foreign secretary, said at a meeting of Community
foreign ministers in Hatfield in the UK that the EC and UN would continue to
press the warring parties to place their heavy weapons under international
control and close down detention camps in Bosnia in compliance with the
London peace conference accords.
Accordingly, Mr John Major, British premier, is to write to the presidents
of Serbia, Bosnia and Croatia reminding them of their obligations.
Ministers agreed to support a US proposal to impose a a 'no fly' zone over
Bosnia-Hercegovina and said Serbia should be denied the former Yugoslavia's
seat at the UN. The proposed ban would not be imposed in the air, as in
Iraq, but by stationing observers at airports.
