<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Shake-up alters shape of politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH and WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LAST night's realignment involves a devaluation of only one currency in the
European Monetary System (EMS). But the adjustment may turn out to have a
more substantial impact than any of the 12 previous shake-ups since the EMS
started in 1979.
The realignment seems likely to bring a seismic shift in Europe's political
and economic landscape only six days away from the French referendum on
Maastricht.
The chances of a Yes vote in France next Sunday seem likely to be improved
if, as is likely, the Bank of France cuts interest rates after this
morning's expected Bundesbank reduction.
Mr Michel Sapin, the French finance minister, said the Bundesbank's desire
to cut rates 'shows real solidarity by Germany towards its European partners
and opens the way to a relaxation of interest rates in Europe, which is
necessary to support growth and unemployment'.
Additionally, by taking action to deal with the over-valuation of the lira,
EC finance ministers have, for the moment at least, defused the most
important source of instability in the EMS.
Currency market jitters will not come to an end as long as the world economy
remains stuck in a slow growth phase, and doubts are maintained over the
eventual fate of the Maastricht treaty. But Europe's exchange rate
stabilisation scheme seems likely to have won sufficient breathing space to
enable it to live to fight another day.
The German government last night stressed that the realignment and expected
Bundesbank credit easing back up Bonn's overall 'European policies'.
In Paris, observers said they believed the move could allay public fears,
expressed in opinion polls, of a German economic domination of Europe.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the Bundesbank president, who was closely involved in
realignment telephone conversations, may have some explaining to do over the
apparent U-turn in the central bank's monetary policies.
In an unprecedented fashion, the Bundesbank has bargained away a cut in its
interest rates in return for the goal  - an EMS realignment  - it has
desired to see for at least two years.
Three factors seem to explain the Bundesbank's volte face.
First, Mr Schlesinger probably believes that the inflationary risks of large
inflows of speculative currency  - which should now cease  - are at least as
large as those of an interest rate cut. Second, the Bundesbank itself has
been concerned by growing signs of domestic recession.
Third, when put under pressure from the Bonn government  - which has been
unhappy for some time over the bank's tight policies  - the Bundesbank does
have a track record of reacting with great pragmatism.
The Bundesbank's reputation for independence is well known. But its last
reduction in discount rate  - a  1/2 point cut to 2 1/2 per cent on December
3 1987  - came after a telephone plea for action by Chancellor Helmut Kohl
to Mr Karl Otto Pohl, the then president. The Bundesbank knows how to stand
firm  - but it also has an instinct for the occasional need, when faced with
overwhelming odds, to make a tactical retreat.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-3133</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CINBUABFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920914
</DATE>
