<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / A weekend of telephone calls across Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, PETER MARSH and DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MASSIVE and futile intervention by the Bank of Italy and the German
Bundesbank last Friday to support the lira triggered the surprise weekend
devaluation of the Italian currency.
After the lira had twice fallen below its D-Mark floor of L765.4 in the
exchange rate mechanism on Friday, it had become clear to the Bundesbank's
currency traders in Frankfurt that the Italian currency would not lift off
the bottom of the ERM in spite of extremely heavy buying by the German
central bank.
Their reports to the Bundesbank directorate came after weeks of mounting
tension in the ERM. There followed a weekend of intensive phone calls across
Europe that culminated in the first significant change in the ERM for more
than five years.
The intervention was a new headache for Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the
Bundesbank's president. Only a week before, at a press conference after a
meeting of European Community finance ministers in Bath, he had indicated
that the scale of intervention to contain strains in the ERM was not yet
posing serious problems for the Bundesbank. By last Friday, German buying of
the lira had become so great as to threaten further increases in Germany's
already swollen money supply.
Mr Schlesinger's reaction on Friday was to discuss the problem with Mr Carlo
Ciampi, the Italian central bank governor, who was experiencing a
haemorrhaging of Italy's foreign currency reserves. At about the same time,
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, and Mr Horst Kohler, the state
secretary in the finance ministry, became involved in consultations.
German officials said there had been a growing feeling from Thursday onwards
that a realignment of the European exchange rate mechanism would be needed
to deal with a 'very considerable' flow of funds from the Italian lira to
the D-Mark. Probably by Friday evening, and certainly by Saturday morning,
Germany was proposing a realignment of the Italian lira and German interest
rate cuts.
The Bundesbank was also motivated to act in expectation that the government
in Bonn and both sides of industry would take more effective measures to
curb inflationary pressures in Germany.
During Saturday morning Mr Schlesinger also contacted the Bundesbank's
regional central bank presidents to prepare them for a special meeting of
the Bundesbank's central council today at 9am Frankfurt time. Mr Schlesinger
wants the council to discuss cuts in Germany's discount and Lombard rates
from 8.75 and 9.75 per cent respectively.
By Saturday afternoon, the apparatus of the European Community was involved
in the plan through Mr Jean-Claude Trichet, director of the French Treasury,
who also chairs the EC's monetary committee. It was around this time that
the UK Treasury was informed of the plan. Sir Nigel Wicks, the Treasury's
second permanent secretary for international monetary affairs and a member
of the monetary committee, passed news of the planned 'double whammy' to Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor.
Over the weekend, Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton and Mr Eddie George, Bank of
England governor and deputy governor, were brought into discussions.
Mr Giuliano Amato, the Italian prime minister, met his economic ministers on
Sunday. He said he had been in touch with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, the
governors of the Bundesbank and the Bank of Italy as well as the German
finance minister and treasury minister to co-ordinate the operation.
Yesterday evening, the move was announced in a communique from the monetary
committee.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
