<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Textile trade rules are attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADE AGREEMENTS on textiles and clothing cost the UK more than Pounds 1bn a
year, according to a report published today.
The Multi-Fibre Arrangement - rules that specify the amount and types of
clothing and textiles to be exported by Third World countries to
industrialised consumers - raises prices and reduces competition, says the
World Development Movement, the pressure group.
Consumers are forced to buy expensive, domestically made clothes while
manufacturing is partly shielded from inexpensive competition. In addition,
poorer consumers have less choice of cheaper clothing.
The report says that the MFA has 'also failed to protect UK jobs. Over
780,000 UK jobs in the textiles industry were lost between 1963 and 1987.'
Most were lost through recession, the introduction of new technology and
competition from elsewhere in the European Community rather than the Third
World.
Threadbare. How the rich stitch up the world's rag trade. WDM, 25 Beehive
Place, London SW9 7QR. Pounds 3.99.
</TEXT>
