FT  14 SEP 92 / Status of independent schools 'must be scrutinised'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN END TO the charitable status of independent schools that do not fulfil a
genuinely charitable function was approved by the Liberal Democrats
yesterday, against the proposal in a party discussion document that it
should be maintained for all of them, Alison Smith writes.
The policy paper, Excellence For All, said that independent schools should
still be able to benefit from charitable status, but that they should meet a
minimum curriculum entitlement and should play a more active part in the
local community.
After the debate, Mr Don Foster, Liberal Democrat education spokesman,
brushed aside the adoption of the amendment from the Young Liberal Democrats
as a minor issue: he did not vote on the issue.
Instead, his speech underlined the party's opposition to schools' opting out
of local education authority control, with a call for such moves to be
vigorously resisted throughout the community, in governing bodies and on
local councils as well as in parliament.
The party's policy is to replace LEAs with democratically accountable
education departments to take strategic decisions, while giving schools
themselves greater autonomy.
The pledge to raise income tax to spend more on education was a distinctive
feature of the Liberal Democrats' general election campaign.
Mr Foster accused the government of being 'out of control' in its attitude
towards education. 'They are behaving like a demented Basil Fawlty,
furiously beating with a large branch a car that doesn't work - in a manic
attempt to get it going.'
