FT  14 SEP 92 / Revival scheme failings identified
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LACK of co-ordination among schemes for promoting economic regeneration has
been criticised at a Business in the Community conference on development in
the east Midlands.
Mr David Grayson, managing director of Business in the Community's strategy
group, said the UK led the world in the number of regeneration schemes it
produced, but they were often unco-ordinated.
He listed several factors that could thwart efforts to revive a rundown
area. They included unrealistic timescales and funding, and the adoption of
too many different priorities. Experience elsewhere in Europe suggested that
organisations involved in regeneration should have firm agreements on their
respective roles and should pool their resources towards a few defined
goals.
His complaints were echoed by Mr Mick Lyons, chief executive of
Nottinghamshire County Council. He said: 'There is too much worry about
setting up new agencies rather than getting existing agencies to work
together.'
He said economic development could not be done by the public sector alone or
without public-sector input.
Mr Philip Champ, a main board director at East Midlands Electricity, warned
that 'no business can continue to thrive in an area where other business is
not doing well'.
