FT  14 SEP 92 / Training guidelines attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DRAFT government guidelines for training policy next year show that Training
and Enterprise Councils and Local Enterprise Councils, their Scottish
counterparts, are expected to lead local initiatives on training targets and
to extract more private-sector funds to support training, Ian Hamilton Fazey
writes.
A scathing response from the Merseyside Tec says the government has ignored
its own leadership role and that Tecs need more public funding. They are
willing to be partners but cannot lead effectively when many of their
objectives concern areas outside their influence.
The draft of the guidelines - to be published late this year - and the
Merseyside response reveal sharp divergences on objectives, how to achieve
them, and the roles of the Tecs.
A member of another Tec board said: 'The Merseyside commentary articulates
what very many of us are feeling. I am sure many other Tecs are preparing
similar responses.'
The government wants all employees to be undergoing training or development
by 1996, when it says half the national workforce should be aiming for basic
national vocational qualifications or 'learning units' towards them. By the
following year, 80 per cent of young people should have basic NVQs.
Merseyside's response states: 'Quality foundation learning for young people
is the responsibility of us all and should be resourced by the nation
through the public purse. It should not be dependent upon the willingness
and capacity of employers to support education initiatives and youth
training.'
It adds that current funding levels, especially in youth training, will not
enable the government's aims to be met.
