<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / MMC to hear of clustered private medical fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INFORMATION to be submitted to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission inquiry
on private medical fees shows evidence that doctors' charges cluster very
closely around the guideline rates published by the British Medical
Association.
An analysis conducted for the Financial Times by Private Patients Plan Group
(PPP), the UK's second-largest private medical insurer, shows relatively
little variation in bills submitted to the company for the same treatment
from doctors around the country.
Last Tuesday the MMC announced that it would investigate the process by
which specialists calculated fees for private patients. It wants to
determine whether there is - voluntarily or involuntarily - a monopoly being
operated between doctors and the BMA.
The BMA first issued a set of guidelines to its members in 1989, which
showed the average rates charged for a series of medical procedures and
anaesthetics. The latest version, published this month, lists rates for more
than 1,500 treatments.
It emphasises that the rates are not 'recommended' levels but simply
advisory information that should help doctors determine their own rates in
discussion with patients.
The PPP analysis - using claims between April 1 and September 9 this year -
shows a wide range between the highest and lowest charges for any type of
treatment. However, the vast majority of bills are concentrated in a small
central range around the levels in the BMA guidelines.
Mr Roy Forman, PPP chief executive, has opposed the idea of a BMA schedule
since it was originated in the 1980s. He welcomed the MMC inquiry, and
argued that since 1989 doctors' fees had risen and increasingly clustered
around the rates published by the BMA.
A separate analysis by the company shows that the increase in claims among
all private health insurers between 1990 and last year has been more than
twice the rate of inflation.
More than 84 per cent of the increase was due to a rise in the value of
claims, with a small increase in the number of claims and a slight decline
in the number of subscribers to private health care plans.
PPP will be submitting further details of the medical bills it receives to
the MMC.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
