<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Ministers face spending squeeze to meet targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Treasury will tell cabinet ministers this week that there must be sharp
cuts in departmental spending programmes if the government is to meet its
stated targets for public expenditure in the next financial year.
Negotiations over the government's 1993-94 spending programme will start at
a meeting of the cabinet's public expenditure committee, which convenes for
the first time on Thursday.
Ministers have already said they will keep to the Pounds 244.5bn planning
total for government expenditure set out in the Budget in March. But since
then the economy has grown more slowly than the government expected, and the
rise in the numbers claiming unemployment benefit will take a larger share
of the public purse than forecast.
Thursday's meeting, to be chaired by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, will
be held against a background of rising concern about the immediate prospects
for the UK economy.
Many UK economic indicators are due out this week, all of them likely to
underline the weakness in the UK economy. Ministers are bracing themselves
for another sharp rise in unemployment when the latest statistics are
released on Thursday. July's industrial production figure, due out on the
same day, is likely to show a modest upturn at best.
As ministers prepare to divide up the public expenditure planning total for
next year, they have been told to expect a tough squeeze on public sector
pay. A final pay norm has not yet been set, but the expected fall in UK
inflation over the next year could mean average public sector pay rises are
about 2 per cent in 1993-94.
A severe squeeze on public investment in housing, roads, the inner cities
and other construction projects is also expected.
Some of the projects that have been under Treasury review - including a
three-year programme to invest Pounds 7bn in motorways and trunk roads -
appear-ed as pledges in the Conservative manifesto. But the Treasury is
arguing that nothing can be immune from scrutiny because of the threat to
the economy posed by soaring public debt.
Anthony Harris, Page 21
Currencies, Page 29
