FT  14 SEP 92 / Cadbury plan for monitoring directors may be changed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TWO most significant proposals in a report aimed at improving the
performance of corporate boards in Britain may have to be changed, said Sir
Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the committee which drew up the recommendations.
The proposals which face alteration would oblige non-executive directors to
monitor the activities of executives, and introduce an enforcement
mechanism.
The draft report of the Committee on the Financial Aspects of Corporate
Governance, published in May, suggested a voluntary code of practice for
boards of directors.
It also urged a new Stock Exchange listing requirement compelling companies
to disclose the extent to which they complied with the code, and to explain
where they did not.
Sir Adrian said more than 200 comments had been received since the draft
report was published. Almost all supported its broad principles though
several recommendations had been criticised.
'There is a great issue about the weight of the role assigned to
non-executives. The question they raise is whether we would be dividing the
board,' Sir Adrian said. 'We have used the word 'monitor'. People have
questioned that.'
He also said some respondents had objected to proposals that the
non-executive chairmen of the audit and remuneration committees should
answer shareholder questions at annual general meetings.
While he stopped short of saying the committee would have to alter its
original proposals, he said those sections of the report would have to be
reviewed closely. A final version of the report is expected to be released
in early November.
The Confederation of British Industry, in particular, has objected to the
enforcement proposals in the Cadbury report, saying they could lead to
unnecessary bureaucracy. Sir Adrian said he believed obtaining the CBI's
support for the report would be critical to its success because its members
had to carry out its proposals voluntarily. 'We need the support of the
CBI,' he said.
Cadbury responds to CBI hostility, Page 10
