<DOCNO>FT923-3192</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CINBUAEHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920914
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Leading Article: ERM adjusts to the strain
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A WEEK may not be a long time in politics, but it is in the foreign exchange
markets. Just over a week ago, at their meeting in Bath, European Community
finance ministers announced their opposition to realignment. Now they have
had to concede one. In Bath they also made loud calls for lower German
interest rates. Now they have obtained them. Thus the 7 per cent devaluation
of the Italian lira, combined with the Bundesbank's commitment to reduce
German interest rates today, looks a sensible compromise. It is also the
least that could have been done. Whether it proves enough depends on
decisions still to be announced.
That the authors of the volte face were Germany and Italy is not surprising,
since these countries are probably the most relaxed about parity
adjustments. Nevertheless, the deal is potentially dangerous, especially for
Italy. Devaluation was probably unavoidable when short-term rates of
interest had been driven to 15 per cent and the country may have lost more
than half its reserves since the beginning of the summer. But devaluation
will do little for economic growth in the short term and may not permit
lower interest rates either.
Licking their wounds at the loss they have just suffered as a result of the
devaluation, creditors of the Italian state are likely to baulk at annual
increases in their outstanding loans of 10 per cent of gross domestic
product, or more. The Italian parliament must give Prime Minister Giuliano
Amato emergency powers to impose budget stringency. If it refuses, it will
have sown the wind. Italy will then reap the inflationary whirlwind.
Credibility fears
Germany too faces new dangers. For the ERM as a whole, much depends on
whether the interest rate reduction apparently promised by the Bundesbank
turns out to be notional, or substantial, and whether it looks like being
the first of a series, or an isolated event. For countries such as the UK,
or even France, significantly less pressure on parities demands the prospect
of substantial and sustained cuts in German interest rates. But such cuts
might damage the Bundesbank.
The German central bank was evidently terrified of continuing the already
costly short term intervention in support of the lira. But if the price it
pays for lira realignment is premature cuts in domestic interest rates, its
credibility could be impaired, especially after its recent reaffirmation of
domestic monetary targeting.
Such a weakening of the Bundesbank is in nobody's long run interests. Should
German interest rate reductions be large, therefore, it will be still more
imperative for the German government to make a serious - not, as now,
largely fictitious - effort to limit the growing indebtedness of the German
state.
Boost to treaty
The French government is naturally delighted at the prospect of lower German
interest rates and hopes for lower French rates too. Less than a week before
the referendum on the Maastricht treaty, such reductions might well tip the
electoral scales. Even if French interest rates cannot be reduced at once,
the government will be able to present the helpful stance of the Germans as
an indication of the value of European co-operation, while warning that such
cooperation would be threatened by a 'non'.
If the scale and presentation of the German interest rate reduction is
important for France, it is vital for the UK. First the floating of the
Finnish markka, then the pressure on the Swedish krona and now, in the heart
of the ERM, the parity of the lira is changed. The pound is likely to be
next in the firing line. Should the German interest rate cut appear to be a
token, pressure to raise UK interest rates, maybe sharply, could be severe.
Especially with the Conservative party conference coming up soon, the
government is bound to find the possibility of higher interest rates
horrifying. But now that markets have been reminded that the ERM is a system
of fixed, but adjustable, exchange rates, they are likely to draw the
obvious conclusion for other currencies.
The immediate UK problem is the level of interest rates, not the exchange
rate against the D-Mark. But a small parity adjustment like that of Italy is
most unlikely to help reduce interest rates. A government determined to stay
in the ERM will have to do what is necessary, while hoping that what the
Bundesbank does proves enough to save it from the higher interest rates it
dreads.
</TEXT>
