<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Bundesbank bows to external pressures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL and ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank's agreement to cut its official interest rates today to
support the realignment within the European Monetary System was seen in
Germany last night as sensational and unprecedented.
It would appear to be the biggest concession made in the history of the bank
 - admitting the limitations of its independence, a legal position
guaranteed by the German constitution.
No commentators or official spokesmen were prepared to admit that the
interest rate cut would be automatic, and it seems likely to be fiercely
debated within the central bank's governing council.
Yet it also seems impossible to believe that Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the
Bundesbank president, and Mr Hans Tietmeyer, deputy president, could agree
to an interest rate cut without being sure they could gain a majority in the
council.
The Bundesbank last night would only confirm that an extraordinary meeting
of the council would be held at 9am today. Spokesmen refused to speculate on
how big the expected cut in discount and Lombard rates would be.
The move reveals the quite extraordinary pressure, from within and outside
Germany, which the central bank has been under to relax its harsh monetary
policy  - because of implications for German economic growth, economic
recovery in Europe, and the wider international economy.
Hitherto, the Bundesbank directors have been adamant that their policy was
dictated solely by the need to curb monetary expansion in Germany, stabilise
inflation, and ensure the stability of the D-Mark.
Only last Thursday, Mr Otmar Issing, a leading member of the executive
council, insisted the bank would not be deflected by outside criticism from
its policy of pursuing firm monetary targets. The strategy was 'without any
convincing alternative'.
And yet the bank has been unable to ignore the turmoil in the currency
markets  - leading last night to the devaluation of the lira  - as, in part,
a consequence of its own high interest rate policy. The differential, above
all, with US interest rates has been a key element driving currency
speculation, aggravated by perceived differences in strength between EMS
members.
Mr Peter Pietsch, an economist with Commerzbank, said the central bank's
move was a 'real sensation'. There was no previous example of such a move,
although there had been both political pressure, and great currency
turbulence, in the past. 'It is a 180 degree turn, very hard to understand,'
he said. 'It is incredible that the Bundesbank is ready to call an emergency
meeting.'
The argument in recent days, however, was that the central bank could no
longer conduct its policies as if in isolation from the rest of the European
and world economy  - and the currency markets have forced the point home.
Pressure for a realignment of the currencies in the Exchange Rate Mechanism
of the EMS had become well-nigh irresistible.
On the other hand, the German government had been against a revaluation on
the grounds that a stronger D-Mark would make any recovery of German exports
even more difficult.
Thus the bank must have come under concerted pressure in recent weeks not
just from other banks and finance ministers in Europe, but from the
government in Bonn.
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, made his relief perfectly clear
last night when he said an interest rate cut would 'improve the
preconditions for a strengthening of economic growth in both Germany and
Europe. Positive pulses will also go out to the world economy.'
'The reason for lower interest rates would be better inflation prospects and
a weakening west German economy,' said Mr James Cornish, an economist at
County NatWest of the UK, who visited the Bundesbank last week. It was not
possible to say yet whether the economy was in a temporary dip or sliding
into recession, he added.
The apparent willingness of the Bundesbank to compromise its reputation for
absolute and often bloody-minded independence will also worry those in
Germany who fear for the future political influence on a single European
central bank.
Germany has hitherto been adamant that such a successor to the Bundesbank
must, if anything, be more independent of political considerations; for
example, coming from ministers of finance in the EC Council of Ministers.
France, on the other hand, and President Francois Mitterrand in particular,
has made it clear that the final word on European monetary policy must lie
with the Council of Ministers.
Now it may be argued that the German central bank has already proved unable
to resist the pressures from the European governments.
Its defenders may reply that all it is doing is responding to the
irresistible pressures of the currency markets, which threatened to undo its
own good work in seeking to curb German monetary growth.
