<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Brief respite for Italy's coalition government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE realignment of the lira within the European Monetary System (EMS) agreed
yesterday is likely to give Italy's four-party coalition government only a
brief respite to demonstrate its ability to tackle the country's
deteriorating public finances.
This breathing space could last until little more than the end of the month,
according to market analysts. Even that could prove optimistic if the French
referendum on Maastricht on September 20 shows a rejection of the treaty.
Ministers also recognise an internationally credible 1993 budget must be
prepared as soon as possible. This depends on parliament approving outline
plans for reforms of pensions, the health service, local government and the
civil service.
The budget has to be presented to parliament by September 30  - but it is
still not clear if and when both the Chamber of Deputies and Senate will
endorse these reforms.
The debate has been clouded by the decision on Wednesday of Prof Giuliano
Amato, the prime minister, to submit a law to enable the government to
invoke emergency economic powers in the event of an economic crisis. Since
the idea was launched, politicians have been voicing increasing
reservations, even those within the government coalition.
An editorial over the weekend in the influential daily Corriere della Sera
newspaper said the request for such emergency powers was like the pilot of a
tumbling aircraft asking for new engines. This view was widely echoed by key
officials dealing with the economy.
Prof Amato indicated he was willing to water down his proposal to ensure the
sovereignty of parliament was not infringed on. One suggestion being mooted
was that he would trade the dropping or watering down of the proposal for
parliament's quick endorsement of the outline reforms essential for the
budget's preparation.
The government will now have to confront the consequences of a currency
realignment. Prof Amato last night said keeping inflation under control
would be a priority. Italy's inflation was scheduled to fall to some 4.5 per
cent by year end.
The prime minister added that Italy's foreign trade was mainly conducted in
dollars and the lira had not been realigned against the dollar. He hoped
interest rates would come down: the discount rate is currently at 15 per
cent to defend the lira and every one-point fall reduces the government's
annual borrowing requirement by L15,000bn (Pounds 7bn).
Apart from seeking early evidence of a desire to reduce the budget deficit
now more than 10.5 per cent of gross domestic product, the markets are
likely to continue to press the government to accelerate further the
privatisation process to encourage domestic and international confidence.
Last week the government said it would sell off stakes in Credito Italiano,
one of the top six commercial banks, and Nuovo Pignone, the heavy
engineering subsidiary of ENI, the state oil concern.
Ever since the Amato government took office on June 29, it has been under
pressure to realign Italy's overvalued lira. However, devaluation has been
constantly resisted in the short term for two main reasons.
Italy's European partners were not prepared for a realignment, especially
the British, and until this weekend the French government had rejected
Italian requests to permit a lira devaluation before the Maastricht
referendum. The government regarded devaluation before the 1993 budget as of
only short-term benefit unlikely to convince the markets and risking being
inflationary.
Thus although it has seen a realignment with the first set of conditions
satisfied, the second has yet to be.
The government has taken heart from the concerted European response which
officials last night said should warn the markets that unilateral pressure
on the lira would eventually affect other members.
The Bank of Italy maintains that by calling on unlimited credit from the
Bundesbank, and to a lesser extent from the Belgian central bank, it
reminded the Germans that defending the lira risked creating liquidity
problems at home.
</TEXT>
