<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Sterling still faces hurdles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FULL impact on sterling of yesterday's realignment of the Exchange Rate
Mechanism will only be known after the results of today's special meeting of
the Bundesbank council.
In the weeks before the realignment, foreign exchange dealers had assumed
that a unilateral devaluation of the lira would put renewed pressure on the
British pound.
Their assumption was that devaluation of the Italian currency would
undermine investor confidence in sterling, which is widely regarded as the
second most vulnerable currency in the system.
That vulnerability has not gone away despite last night's events. 'Now that
the lira has been devalued, sterling is the most exposed currency in the
system,' said Mr Gerard Lyons, chief economist at DKB International in
London .
However, a cut in German interest rates would remove what has been the
biggest pressure on sterling until now. With short-term interest rates in
Germany at 9.75 per cent, the Bank of England's policy of keeping base rate
at 10 per cent has provided currency speculators with too small a return on
their investment until now.
'We could get a German cut of 50 basis points or even 100 basis points,'
said Mr Lyons.
But, he added that the size of the reduction was less important than the
move itself. Until now, investors had been anxious that the next move in
German interest rates could be up rather than down. A cut in rates today
would be the first official cut in Germany since 1988, when the Bundesbank
raised the discount rate from 2.5 per cent to 3 per cent.
However, even if there is a one percentage point cut in Germany's Lombard
rate today, sterling will still face a number of hurdles.
The first problem would be new signs that the UK economy is in the grip of
recession.
The outlook for the economy remains weak, with many analysts assuming that
there will be negative growth in the UK this year followed by only a modest
recovery in 1993.
Thursday's monthly unemployment figures for August are almost certain to
show a rise in the number of people out of work, and may check any surge in
confidence that appears today.
Another problem for sterling will be France's referendum on the Maastricht
treaty on Sunday.
Until recently, currency investors had bought weaker EMS currencies such as
sterling and the lira because they assumed that both the UK and Italy would
have to rein in their annual public sector borrowing requirements in order
to meet the convergence criteria set out in the Maastricht treaty.
If the French vote No on Sunday, the markets could assume that European
Monetary Union is dead and will unwind their earlier investments.
'If the French reject Maastricht, then this realignment will have done
little to stabilise the tensions in the EMS,' said Mr Jim O'Neill, head of
research at Swiss Banking Corporation in London.
As they tried to absorb last night's dramatic events, some analysts were
confident that the immediate outlook for the pound was promising.
'Sterling will rally on Monday morning, but it is not yet clear by much,'
said Mr John Shepperd, an economics analyst at S G Warburg in London.
'The domestic money markets were discounting a rise in UK base rates.
'If the Bundesbank cuts rates, there will be hectic trading as the money
markets shift their position radically. The equity market could rise too.'
