<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Lira devalued 7% in EMS: Bundesbank interest rates to be cut
today UK to maintain sterling-DM parity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign and Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY and Germany last night moved to end the crisis in the European
Monetary System by agreeing an effective 7 per cent devaluation of the lira
to be followed by cuts in the Bundesbank's leading interest rates today.
Monetary officials said the surprise move, agreed by telephone over the
weekend, could be followed by interest rate cuts in other countries such as
France and the Netherlands. Analysts suggested it also could ease
speculative pressure against sterling.
Mr Norman Lamont, the UK chancellor, last night welcomed the realignment and
in particular the Bundesbank's intention to cut its interest rates.
In a statement, he made clear Britain would not alter the parity of sterling
against the D-Mark and that it would take 'whatever action was necessary' to
maintain the central rate at DM2.95.
The chancellor said last night's moves demonstrated the 'benefits of
continuing close co-operation among Community countries'.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, urged Mr Lamont to cut UK interest rates
and take measures to boost employment and investment to restore economic
growth.
Announcing the EMS changes in Brussels, the EC monetary committee said all
currencies would be revalued by 3.5 per cent, except the lira which would be
devalued by 3.5 per cent. The moves were initiated after massive
intervention by the Bundesbank and the Bank of Italy on Friday failed to
lift the currency off its floor against the D-Mark in the European exchange
rate mechanism. The Bundesbank spent well over the DM2.5bn that it published
for intervention last week.
The intervention, obligatory under the rules of the ERM, had the effect of
increasing Germany's monetary reserves and so threatening to add to its
already rapid money supply growth.
The German interest rate cuts will be decided at an unprecedented meeting of
the Bundesbank's ruling council at 9am Central European Time today. A
Bundesbank official said last night both the discount and Lombard rates,
currently 8.75 and 9.75 per cent respectively, would be cut.
EC officials said the Bundesbank appeared to have agreed to cut its interest
rates in expectation that the Bonn government and both sides of industry
would take more effective measures to curb inflationary pressures in
Germany. It also seems to have become more worried about the slowdown in the
German economy than was the case only a week ago at the EC finance
ministers' meeting in Bath.
Prof Giuliano Amato, the Italian prime minister, last night put a brave face
on events, saying he believed the decision effectively to devalue by 7 per
cent would not be inflationary.
The main component in Italy's inflation was internal costs, he said, and the
government was seeking to tackle these. Italy's inflation has been falling
and in August was running at 5.3 per cent on an annual basis.
Prof Amato said he welcomed the co-operation of the Germans and the
agreement worked out in consultation with other EC members. 'If we had
devalued earlier, it would have been merely an own goal,' he said.
The impact of the realignment was immediately felt this morning in the
Pacific markets where trading was described as frantic. In Tokyo the dollar
opened sharply higher against the D-Mark. It was trading close to DM1.50
after closing at DM1.4508 in New York on Friday. Sterling was trading above
DM2.82, against its previous London close of DM2.79. Against the dollar it
had fallen to below Dollars 1.89 after Friday's New York close of Dollars
1.921.
The Bundesbank's agreement to cut its official rates will amount to a
substantial concession by the central bank, in effect giving in to pressure
from the other member states in the EMS.
Until now, the Bundesbank has been adamant that its high interest rate
policy is essential to curb monetary expansion and hold down inflation
within Germany. By agreeing to make cuts, it is admitting the important role
the high rates have played in the recent European currency market turmoil.
Only last week Mr Otmar Issing, a leading Bundesbank board member, insisted
that the bank's interest rate policy would not be swayed by broader economic
considerations, but only by its paramount task to curb inflation and
maintain the D-Mark's stability.
Nonetheless, pressure on the Bundesbank has been growing rapidly both within
Germany, and outside it, to recognise the international reality causing the
stresses in the currency markets.
The German decision may fuel hopes of rate cuts in the US and Japan.
The EMS changes were welcomed by the US where Mr Nicholas Brady, treasury
secretary, said they were a 'positive development for world markets'.
In London, several City economists said the Bundesbank's pledge could lead
to a rise of sterling and other European currencies today, and that, in the
short term, the pressure had been taken off the UK to raise rates.
Mr John Shepperd, senior economist at Warburgs, said the chief part of the
equation was still missing - namely the size of the German rates cut.
But he added: 'The most important thing is that the Bundesbank has cracked.
It has bowed to international pressure, abandoning domestic issues. Its
approach to policy has changed. In the future it is likely to have a much
more accommodating stance. There will be much more confidence that the
current parities will be much more durable and sustainable. What was going
to blow the ERM apart was the Bundesbank's intransigence.'
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
said the Bundesbank move was 'very welcome'. He hoped the cuts in German
borrowing rates would be followed by UK interest rate cuts 'at an early
stage'.
The lira has been under pressure since the Danish referendum on Maastricht,
but this intensified over the past two weeks as a result of two factors:
uncertainties about the outcome of the French referendum on Maastricht and
market fears that the Italian government would not take sufficiently tough
measures to tackle the country's budget deficit rising beyond 10.5 per cent
of gross domestic product.
On August 8 the lira for the first time breached its L765.40 floor in the
EMS against the D-Mark. Since then it has been close to or near the floor.
According to Prof Amato, the German government last week initiated secret
contacts with the treasury and the Bank of Italy on a realignment of
currencies in the EMS. The Italian government lobbied hard for the
Bundesbank to realign in conjunction with a lowering of its own interest
rates.
Italian officials indicated that a significant element influencing German
attitudes was the increasing number of calls likely to be made on the
Bundesbank to buy lire under its EMS obligations to support weaker
currencies.
Already this month the Bundesbank had been obliged to drain liquidity from
the domestic market to back its lira support operations. Last Friday and the
previous Friday the Bundesbank bought lire worth a total of more than
DM1.7bn.
On the Italian side, the authorities had few weapons left to confront
another week of speculation against the lira in the run-up to the French
referendum. Unofficial estimates of convertible foreign currency reserves
are believed to be little more than L10,000bn against L26,000bn at the end
of July.
The discount rate was raised by 1.75 points to 15 per cent on September 3
and overnight money rates on Friday rose to 28 per cent.
Last night there was no indication the Italian authorities would be able to
lower the discount rate. This suggested they would watch market reactions
which are still thought likely to be nervous about the lira.
