<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / UK Gilts: Traders on tenterhooks after devaluation of lira
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE gilt market will be on tenterhooks today as all eyes focus on the
Bundesbank and the size of the cut in interest rates it has indicated it
will make after last night's devaluation of the Italian lira.
From the point of view of sterling, the developments are both good and bad
news. A cut in German borrowing rates - the size and nature of which are due
to be announced today - should take the pressure off the pound in the
European exchange rate mechanism grid.
On the other hand, a lira devaluation - the first significant adjustment of
the ERM since 1987 - might appear in the eyes of some market participants to
presage other changes in parities in the grid affecting other weak
currencies, the pound included.
The markets also have to digest the outcome of next Sunday's referendum on
Maastricht. If France votes No to European economic and monetary union, that
could lead to further selling pressure on weak ERM currencies, exacerbating
the recent strains on currency markets and possibly leading ultimately to a
sterling devaluation.
The general nervousness about the pound was a feature of gilt trading last
week. It forced a large rise in yields for short-dated bonds, amid fears
that the British government might be forced, in the near future, to increase
interest rates to defend the pound's ERM parity.
With the UK government stressing strongly last week it would not devalue the
pound, a rise in base rates, now 10 per cent, might be required to prevent
sterling falling through its ERM floor.
That explained why the yield on the short-dated 8 3/4 per cent Treasury bond
due in 1997 rose  1/3 of a percentage point last week, closing on Friday
night at 9.71 per cent. Its price fell by 1 point to 96 7/32 .
While short yields were pushed up, few large sellers of the securities were
reported. An exception, however, was the Bank of Sweden, which was said to
be selling gilts for cash to put its foreign-currency reserves in a more
liquid state in case large-scale intervention is required to defend the
beleaguered krona.
At the long end of the yield curve, investors such as pension funds and
insurance companies were moderate buyers of gilts on optimistic perceptions
about the longer term inflation profile. As a result, long-gilt yields were
depressed marginally.
The degree to which pressure on rising prices is becoming subdued as a
result of the long recession was underlined by last week's figures for the
retail prices index. The RPI rose by 3.6 per cent in the year to August,
after 3.7 per cent in the 12 months to July.
However, it was the shorter term outlook for the pound that worried most
gilt investors last week. Sterling closed on Friday against the D-Mark at
DM2.79, slightly more than 1 pfennig above its DM2.778 ERM floor. This was
even though a stronger dollar somewhat eased the overall ERM strains by
putting less upward pressure on the German currency. A weak pound depresses
sentiment about gilts.
A special problem for the pound is the stalled domestic economy. With some
commentators suggesting a recovery is unlikely until 1993 or 1994, investors
are unlikely to want to push funds into sterling on the basis of hopes about
a growing economy.
At the same time, the UK's economic weakness greatly magnifies the potential
effects of Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, being forced to raise base
rates to defend sterling's ERM parity.
'In normal times, the bad news about the economy, and the sense that
inflation is coming down, would be expected to be good news for gilts,' said
Mr James Barty, an economist at Morgan Grenfell. 'The trouble for gilts is
that these are not normal times.'
</TEXT>
