<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / European Bonds: German interest rate cut to spark volatile
trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TODAY'S promised cut in German interest rates will kick off a week of
volatile trading in European government bond markets in the run up the
French referendum on the Maastricht treaty. German yields, which were
already falling last week as investors switched out of higher yielding
paper, could now be set to fall sharply.
The bond markets will be looking closely to the foreign exchange markets for
their lead this morning. The central question for both markets is likely to
be the scale of the promised German cut in interest rates. If speculators
judge the cut too small, they will have a perfect excuse to launch further
attacks on weaker currencies, principally sterling. They have been proved
right once, so why shouldn't the same trick work a second time?
But if the Bundesbank's cut is a substantial one, the ERM could yet end the
week stronger than it started. Most analysts had given up hope of any
significant German interest rate cut before the end of this year, so an
earlier move could take the pressure off Germany's neighbours, possibly
allowing them scope for interest rate cuts.
Yesterday's monetary developments will influence the French referendum on
Maastricht: if French interest rates fall this week, as the Italian
government, at least, was suggesting last night, French voters may be more
willing to give European monetary union the benefit of the doubt.
If, despite this, France votes No, today's piece of damage limitation from
the German authorities could be quickly forgotten. Before the weekend's
excitements, some analysts were suggesting that bond markets in the D-Mark
bloc should benefit from either result. Their arguments hold good, in
modified form, even after Sunday's realignment.
A No vote would raise the question of whether the lira had been sufficiently
devalued, and perhaps call the pound's ERM rates into question. Both of
these concerns would probably lead to outperformance by the German bond
market - or at least, a predisposition by investors already in the D-Mark
bloc to stay put.
A Yes vote, on the other hand, would trigger a rally in the higher-yielding
French, Spanish and Ecu bond markets, while the D-Mark bloc would initially
be left behind. But since a Yes vote in France would still leave many
questions unanswered about the future of the Maastricht treaty, some
economists recommend taking early profits in higher-yielding markets and
going overweight in bunds.
German bond yields fell last week on the growing belief that the Bundesbank
would eventually respond to the slowing domestic economy by cutting interest
rates. The yield on the benchmark 8 per cent 2002 bond dropping to 7.82 per
cent from 7.74 per cent. This compares with 8.13 per cent at the end of
July. Yields on shorter maturities showed a bigger drop last week, of around
12 basis points.
Last night's confirmation of what on Friday was no more than wishful
thinking should fuel the rally in bunds. Its extent, however, depends on the
size of the cut.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
